{"cursor":"20444","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n{{Infobox character |series = Thomas & Friends |name = Thomas the Tank Engine\n|image = |first = Thomas the Tank Engine (The Railway Series) \"Thomas &\nGordon\" (Thomas and Friends) |creator = Wilbert Awdry Christopher Awdry\n|portrayer = Martin Sherman (US) Ben Small (UK) Edward Glen (Thomas\nand the Magic Railroad) John Bellis (Film cut only) Ringo Starr\n(The Official BBC Children in Need Medley) |gender = \"Male\" |lbl1 = Number\n|data1 = 1 }}\n\n'Thomas the Tank Engine' is a fictional steam locomotive in The Railway Series\nbooks by the Reverend Wilbert Awdry and his son, Christopher. He became the most\npopular character in the series, and the accompanying television spin-off\nseries, [[Thomas the Tank Engine & Friends]].\n\nThomas is a tank engine, painted blue with red lining, and displays the running\nnumber one. All of the locomotives in The Railway Series were based on\nprototypical engines; Thomas has origins in the E2 Class designed by Lawson\nBillinton in 1913.\n\nThomas first appeared in 1946 in the second book in the series, [[List of\nRailway Series books#Thomas the Tank Engine|Thomas the Tank Engine]], and was\nthe focus of the four short stories contained within.\n\nIn 1979, the British writer/producer Britt Allcroft came across the books, {{cite book\n | last = Sibley first = Brian authorlink = Brian Sibley title =[[List of\n | Railway Series Books#The Thomas the Tank Engine Man|The Thomas the\n | Tank Engine Man]] publisher = Heinemann year = 1995 pages = 291 isbn =\n | 0-434-96909-5\n }} \n and arranged a deal to bring the stories to life as Thomas the Tank Engine\n and Friends (later simplified to Thomas and Friends). The programme became\n an award-winning hit around the world, with a vast range of spin-off\n commercial products.\n","linknr":434,"url":"Thomas_the_Tank_Engine","recorded":1362570024,"links":38,"instances":["fictional","actor"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Fi